<div class="panels" id="panels"></div>

<div class="explanation">
  <h2>📚 Why Bubble Sort Falls Short</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Bubble Sort</strong> works by repeatedly stepping through the list, comparing adjacent elements and
    swapping them if they are in the wrong order. While simple to understand, it performs
    <strong>O(n²)</strong> comparisons and swaps in the average and worst case — meaning doubling the array
    size <em>quadruples</em> the work required.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Merge Sort</strong> uses a divide-and-conquer strategy: split the array in half recursively, sort
    each half, then merge them back together. This guarantees <strong>O(n log n)</strong> in all cases —
    dramatically fewer operations for large arrays.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Quick Sort</strong> picks a pivot element and partitions the array so that smaller elements come
    before it and larger elements after, then recurses on each partition. Average case is
    <strong>O(n log n)</strong> and in practice it is often the fastest due to excellent cache performance.
  </p>

  <table class="complexity-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Algorithm</th>
        <th>Best Case</th>
