## What this does to your colleague's argument

**Three panels race simultaneously** so the performance gap is impossible to ignore:

| Feature | Details |
|---|---|
| **Live counters** | Comparisons, swaps, and total steps update in real-time as bars move |
| **Color coding** | Blue = unsorted, Red = comparing, Orange = swapping, Purple = pivot, Green = sorted |
| **Post-race verdict** | Horizontal bars show the exact comparison ratio (e.g. "Bubble used 47× more comparisons") |
| **Three data modes** | Random, Nearly Sorted (bubble's best case), Reversed (bubble's worst nightmare) |
| **Speed control** | From slow/educational to ludicrous speed |
| **Array size slider** | Crank it up to 120 elements and watch bubble's O(n²) explode |

**The killer move**: set order to **Reversed** at size **120** — bubble sort will rack up thousands of comparisons while merge and quick sort finish in a fraction of the time. Screenshot that verdict panel and send it to your colleague.

